Can you help me understand how enterprise e-sign platforms typically work? We're evaluating options for our vendor NDA process.

--- Turn 1 Assistant ---
Happy to walk through this. Here's how enterprise e-sign platforms (DocuSign, Adobe Acrobat Sign, Dropbox Sign, Ironclad CLM with signature, etc.) typically work, especially in the context of a vendor NDA process:

## Core workflow

1. **Document preparation** — You upload a PDF/Word template or pull from a CLM. The platform lets you drop "fields" (signature, initials, date, text, checkbox) and assign each to a specific signer role (e.g., "ContosoAI signatory," "Vendor signatory").
2. **Envelope creation** — An "envelope" bundles the document(s), signer routing order, and metadata. You add recipients by email, set signing order (serial, parallel, or mixed), and optionally add CC-only viewers or approvers.
3. **Authentication** — Recipients click an emailed link. Depending on configured assurance level, they authenticate via email-only, SMS code, knowledge-based authentication (KBA), ID verification, or SSO.
4. **Signing** — Signers adopt a signature (drawn, typed, or uploaded), click through fields, and submit. The platform records a tamper-evident audit trail.
5. **Completion & distribution** — A signed PDF with an embedded certificate of completion is delivered to all parties and stored.

## Features that matter for vendor NDAs specifically

- **Templates** — Pre-built NDA templates with field mapping so legal ops doesn't re-tag fields every time.
- **Bulk send** — One template → many vendors, each getting a personalized envelope. Useful when onboarding a cohort.
- **PowerForms / self-service links** — A public URL vendors can initiate from, which auto-routes to your signatory. Great for reducing back-and-forth.
- **Conditional logic** — Show/hide fields based on vendor type (e.g., mutual vs. one-way NDA).
- **Reminders & expirations** — Auto-nudge non-signers; auto-void after N days.
- **CLM / contract repo integration** — Syncs executed NDAs to Ironclad, SpotDraft, LinkSquares, SharePoint, Google Drive, or your DMS. Metadata (counterparty, effective date, term) is extracted.
- **API / webhooks** — Trigger envelopes from procurement intake forms (Jira, Workday, Coupa) and post status back.

## Compliance & legal validity

- **ESIGN Act & UETA** (US), **eIDAS** (EU) — Enterprise platforms support Simple, Advanced (AES), and Qualified (QES) electronic signatures. Most US vendor NDAs only require SES; eIDAS may push you toward AES/QES for EU counterparties.
- **Audit trail / certificate of completion** — Captures IP, timestamps, authentication method, signer identity. This is the evidentiary record if enforceability is challenged.
- **SOC 2 Type II, ISO 27001, HIPAA, FedRAMP** — Typical certifications. Check which your security team requires.
- **Data residency** — Important if you have EU/UK vendors (GDPR) or public sector counterparties.

## Evaluation criteria I'd flag

| Criterion | Why it matters for NDAs |
|---|---|
| Template governance | Prevents rogue NDA variants in circulation |
| Routing flexibility | Vendor signs first, then your legal, then CFO countersign |
| Branding | White-labeled emails/signing page build vendor trust |
| API coverage | Lets you automate from procurement intake |
| Pricing model | Per-envelope vs. per-seat vs. unlimited — NDAs are high-volume/low-complexity, so envelope pricing can bite |
| Archival & retrieval | Search by counterparty, effective date, expiration |
| Redlining support | Most e-sign tools don't redline — that's CLM territory. Decide if you need integrated negotiation |

## Common architectures at companies your size

- **Standalone e-sign** (DocuSign/Adobe Sign) + manual upload to Drive/SharePoint — cheapest, most manual.
- **E-sign + lightweight CLM** (Ironclad, LinkSquares, SpotDraft) — templated NDAs, auto-routing, metadata extraction, repository.
- **Embedded in procurement platform** (Coupa CLM, SAP Ariba) — good if procurement drives vendor onboarding.

